The Pope puts the Falklands on the map
Greg Burke, the Vatican's communications adviser, says Pope Francis seems unaware that he has maps in his official residence which refer to the Falklands, rather than the Malvinas, which is how they are referred to in his native Argentina.
Argentine President Cristina Fernandez is pictured meeting Pope Francis Photo: AP	By Tim Walker
7:30AM BST 20 May 2013
Comments
Given his Argentine heritage, it is an issue upon which he has pledged not to pontificate, but Pope Francis may still be unwittingly boosting Britain’s right to the Falkland Islands. Greg Burke, a former Fox News correspondent, who is now the Vatican’s communications adviser, has let it be known that the official maps of the world inside the Apostolic Palace in Rome effectively acknowledge the UK’s sovereignty. Burke says he is “pretty sure” that the venerable elaborate maps, upon which the place names are inscribed in Latin, refer to the South Atlantic archipelago by its British name, the Falklands, rather than the Argentine Malvinas. In a jocular reference to Pope Francis, formerly Cardinal Jorge Bergoglio, the Archbishop of Buenos Aires, Burke says: “I’m wondering if he has seen that.”
At a gathering at Heythrop theological college, organised by the Roman Catholic Bishops’ Conference, Burke admits that he was minded to take photographs of the maps that he saw in his office in the Vatican Secretariat of State, on the third floor of the Apostolic Palace, the so-called the Terza Loggia, close to the papal apartments. “I’ll have to take a photo, I’m pretty sure it is up there – there is a big wall of maps and there is even a second wall of maps, they look quite beautiful. “On the second one I think it says 'Falklands’ and not 'Malvinas’. OK I don’t know when it dates from, but I’m wondering if he [the Pope] has seen that, but I’m pretty sure that [it’s there] – in Latin, but you can make it out.”
