Cristina Fernandez de Kirchner, the Argentine president, has already sought the support of the Pope over her country’s claim to the islands. History does not, alas, relate whether Burke was referring to the frescoes of maps in the entrance hall to the Secretariat of State, which date from the early 16th century – more than 200 years before the islands were settled. Art imitates life for Sarandon
Susan Sarandon has a realistic approach to acting. “I’ve always thought of it as playing,” says the star of the The Big Wedding, which is released later this month. The last time I saw the amiable star was at the chic La Residencia in Majorca. No airs and graces and no entourage. She told me she filmed her role as a character planning a wedding at the same time she was helping her daughter, Eva Amurri, plan hers. “Everyone was very nice to each other, nothing like that wedding in the movie,’’ she noted.
Any takers for English Heritage? The top job at the National Theatre may not be regarded as the glittering prize it once was – Michael Grandage and Danny Boyle etc told me they are not interested in succeeding Sir Nicholas Hytner – but one hopes that there will be some suitable takers for the chairmanship of English Heritage. The Labour peer Baroness Andrews, 70, is stepping down, but presumably not because of the stress of the job. It commands a salary of £40,000-a-year for “up to” two days a week. The blurb says “an outstanding individual with vision and stature” is required. The best known former chairman is undoubtedly Sir Jocelyn Stevens. Joanna’s limits
Joanna Lumley may be a chum of the Duke of Edinburgh – I disclosed how, in 2008, the actress had been quick to go to his hospital bedside as he recovered from a chest infection – but she has no wish to follow Dame Helen Mirren and play the great man’s wife. “I’ve never been asked and I’ve never really thought about it,” Lumley tells me when I raise the subject. She concedes that she has the right diction, and there is an element of typecasting when it comes to posh characters, but she wonders if, even with a lot of make up, she could pull it off. “Acting is pretending, but, even so, I am not particularly similar to her,” she adds. UK News
