Chuck Hagel, the US defence secretary, warned senators that "a refusal to act would undermine the credibility" of the US overseas. "The word of the United States must mean something," said Mr Hagel. "It is vital currency in foreign relations and international and allied commitments". "The United States must demonstrate through our actions that the use of chemical weapons is unacceptable," he added. Mr Hagel, also a Vietnam war veteran, stressed the threat posed by Assad's actions to US allies such as Israel, Turkey and Iraq. "The use of chemical weapons in Syria is not only an assault on humanity – it is a serious threat to America’s national security interests and those of our closest allies," he said. Opening the hearing, Senator Robert Menendez, a Democrat of New Jersey and the committee chairman, said Congress was charged with deciding whether the US would “stand silent in the face of human suffering”. Mr Menendez warned inaction would embolden Iran, North Korea, Hizbollah and Hamas, while “Israel will think we don’t have their back”. As shouting anti-war protesters were hauled out of the Senate hearing, Mr Kerry said he sympathised because he had similar feelings while testifying to the same committee on the war in Vietnam, from which he had just returned, in April 1971, at the age of 27. “That is exactly why it is so important that we are here talking about these things,” he said, but insisted: “This is not the time for armchair isolationism”. Amid concerns from senators that Mr Obama's proposal is too open-ended, Mr Kerry and Gen Martin Dempsey, the chairman of the joint chiefs of staff, stressed the US was not making plans for "boots on the ground". "The task I've been given is to develop military actions that deter Assad and degrade his ability to use chemical weapons," said Gen Dempsey. He conceded that such an attack might also harm Assad's "overall capacities". However Mr Kerry raised eyebrows by requesting that the use of troops not be explicitly ruled out in the proposal in case "Syria implodes" or other catastrophic developments unfold. "I don't want to take off the table an option that might or might not be on the table," he said. Pressed on his remarks, Mr Kerry said he had merely been "thinking out loud" about hypothetical developments but would "shut that door now as tight as we can". "Let me be very clear," Mr Kerry said. “There will not be American boots on the ground with respect to the civil war”. Kerry, Hagel, Dempsey Testify on Use of Force in Syria. (JIM LO SCALZO/EPA)
Earlier, President Barack Obama secured the crucial support of Republican leaders in Congress for military action in Syria, as he promised strikes against Bashar al-Assad's regime would be part of a "broader strategy" to support rebel forces. Having previously insisted a US attack would punish Assad for using chemical weapons but not aim at regime change, Mr Obama stressed for the first time it would "degrade Assad's capabilities" and help end the near three-year conflict. “We have a broader strategy that will allow us to upgrade the capabilities of the opposition, allow Syria ultimately to free itself from the kinds of terrible civil war, death and activity that we’ve been seeing on the ground,” said Mr Obama, as he met congressional leaders at the White House. His new emphasis promptly secured the support of John Boehner, the Republican House Speaker, whose endorsement could be key to the White House’s efforts to convince a sceptical Congress to endorse US military action next week. “I’m going to support the president’s call for action,” he said. White House aides were increasingly optimistic that Mr Obama would get the go-ahead for intervention from Congress, after his former rival Senator John McCain offered to help him avoid a humiliating defeat in exchange for assurances the US would do more to back the rebels. “An authorisation for some limited use of force is all but certain to pass on a bipartisan basis,” a senior Republican Senate aide told The Daily Telegraph. “While anything can happen, it would take some kind of game-changing event to tank the vote in the House.”
Ban Ki-moon, the UN Secretary General, warned military action may only unleash more turmoil. “We must consider the impact of any punitive measure on efforts to prevent further bloodshed and facilitate the political resolution of the conflict,” Mr Ban said. “I call for the Security Council to unite should the allegations prove true.”
Mr Obama signalled he was open to allowing Democratic senators to rewrite the resolution authorising force to explicitly ban the use of US ground troops and include a possible end-date for military action. “This is not Iraq and this is not Afghanistan,” he said. Protestors hold up signs in the hearing room on Capitol Hill in Washington. (J. SCOTT APPLEWHITE/AP)
Members of both parties complained the resolution was too broad and gave the White House a “blank cheque” without setting limits. White House lawyers are ensuring new language does not prevent the US from sending small groups of covert special forces into the country. Mr Obama also stressed failing to punish Syria would embolden Iran and endanger Israel, warning chemical weapons could fall into terrorists’ hands and “pose a risk to allies and friends of ours, like Israel, like Jordan, like Turkey”. After the meeting Mr Boehner said: “We have allies around the world, and allies in the region, who need to know America will be there — and stand up — when necessary.”
“This is behaviour outside the circle of civilised human behaviour,” said Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic minority leader. “And we must respond.”
Mr Obama is in Sweden on Wednesday and will fly on to Russia for the G20 summit, leaving his senior aides and Joe Biden, the vice president, to continuing lobbying members of Congress who remain reluctant to give their support. Representative Tammy Duckworth, an Illinois Democrat like Mr Obama, who lost both her legs when the Black Hawk helicopter she was piloting was shot down during the Iraq war, said of the Syrian opposition: “I don’t know if they are actual rebels or whether they are terrorists. “If I could guarantee that everyone who comes to get weapons that we would provide was actually a legitimate rebel and not al-Qaeda, then I would be more supportive of it”. Ms Duckworth said there was “real reluctance among American leadership, and myself especially, in committing our troops to another endless war”. Several congressmen stressed the US public seemed overwhelmingly to oppose military action and said they were coming under pressure from constituents to block Mr Obama’s plan. “I received 225 emails over the weekend regarding Syria, and out of the 225 only three support US military action,” said Tim Griffin of Arkansas. Chris Murphy, a Democratic Senator for Connecticut, said he had not received so many messages from voters since the divisive battle over Mr Obama’s healthcare overhaul in 2010. Syria
