Nine years on: the children of Beslan
The children who were held hostage by terrorists nine years ago are graduating from high school. All of them remember, but not everyone likes to talk about it. Child of sorrow: Fariza returns to the scene of her ordeal Photo: Oksana Yushko	By Yulia Gutova
5:36PM BST 10 Sep 2013
Read more Russian news and features
Fariza’s parents urged her to study in Moscow but, six months before graduation, she decided to stay in Beslan. She will attend the medical academy in Vladikavkaz. “I know a family that has a lot of children,” says Fariza. “Here they are, smart girls, but they think that they won’t have a future, because the parents simply have no money at all. Why do they keep giving so much just to us? It seems unfair somehow. Seriously.” “We – our class and others – have seen a lot,” says Fariza’s classmate, Amina, smiling. “We took trips to Greece and to America. And we went to Germany and Italy. There were trips to Jordan and to England. And [Fariza] went to school in Moscow.” “Yes,” says Fariza. “We were invited. I went to that school for three years; it was nice, but the kids were mean. I went there in the fifth grade. “Everyone urged me to go. I didn’t want to but I didn’t want to upset my mother. Three years later, I came home in the summer and stayed.” “You know how it is here,” says Amina. “Guests arrive. They go first to the cemetery, to the City of Angels memorial where the Beslan children are buried. Then they go to the gym, where the terrorist attack took place. Our tourist attractions are a cemetery and gymnasium. “So now they are going to start giving out apartments to victims of the terrorist attack. You wouldn’t believe how the adults are behaving – especially the parents of dead children. They are arguing about which floor their apartment will be on. Their children are dead, nobody will return them. Why do this?” “And when I was handing in documents to register at our local technical school, parents were there fighting for a place in line,” Fariza adds, laughing uncomfortably. “Now they don’t let parents inside. Last year, they had a fight inside; this year, it was outside. “There are some families where one child was killed and the other survived, and they are so fixated on the first that they forget about the second child. “Even I am ashamed, Fariza continues, her voice trembling. “I remember how it was, the terrorist attack, and it makes me... I think, if I had been older, I would have helped someone. “When I got out, people around me were wounded. We could have helped them. But we just got out; that's all that was on our minds. “At one point, my brother went and poured water into his shoe and I drank straight from it. My mum asked me for some, but I didn’t give her a drink. I’m so ashamed of it. She says she doesn't remember now.” Hostages were taken at School No 1 in Beslan, North Ossetia, on the morning of September 1, 2004, during a ceremony held to inaugurate the new academic year. For two-and-a-half days, the terrorists held more than 1,100 people – including children, their parents and school staff – in a building filled with explosives. On the third day, there were explosions in the school, and a fire started that caused the building to partially collapse. After the first explosions, the hostages began to run out of the school and security forces stormed the building. During the chaotic shootout that ensued, in which civilians also participated with their own weapons, 27 terrorists were killed. The only terrorist caught alive was sentenced to life in prison. Read more and watch the slideshow at rbth.co.uk
